To connect to a special host (ftp.uni-erlangen.de for example), you should
type
@example
ftp ftp.uni-erlangen.de
@end example
@noindent
The host answers by requesting your login. You should type
@example
ftp
@end example
@noindent
No you are asked for a password. Please type your Email address here, if
you have one. If not, use the password ftp.

Now you're inside the host. There is a number of commands you may execute
here. The most important are:
@table @strong
@item ?
Prints the help text of the FTP command. Additionally you may type
@strong{? command} to get information on a special command.
@item bin
Tells the FTP program that you whish to transfer binary files. It is always
a good choice to type bin as the very first command! Files you load without
the bin command can be corrupt.
@item get <file>
Loads the given file from the host. On most Unix machines you
can type something like @samp{get file.txt -} or @samp{get file.txt |more}
to show a text on the screen. Note that there @strong{must not} be any blank
between the | and the word more!
@item mget <pat>
Loads the given files. pat may contain Unix style like wildcards.
@item put <file>
@itemx mput <pat>
Like get and mget, but transfer files from you to the remote host. This
is in most cases not allowed, except for a special directory called
@file{incoming}. You can place files here which you want to make public.
@item cd <dir>
Like the usual cd command. The commands get, mget, put, mput, dir and ls
refer to the current working directory.
@item dir [<dir>]
@item ls [<dir>]
Like @samp{list} and @samp{dir} on the Amiga. Note that the FTP-dir
corresponds to the Amiga-list!
@item bye
Leaves the FTP program.
@end table

When you have used FTP for the first times you will notice, that you always
begin with executing the same steps:
@enumerate
@item Type the login (ftp in most cases)
@item Type the password (your mail address in most cases)
@item Enter the bin command
@item Change the current working directory (@file{/pub/aminet} for example)
@end enumerate
This may get executed automatically. What you need is a file called
@file{.netrc} in your home directory. Note that it needs to be protected
against others! The FTP program doesn't use it, if it can be read by
anything else than you. (Protection is set using the command
@samp{chmod go-rwx .netrc}.) The .netrc file contains some entries for
your most favourite FTP sites, each separated by empy lines. A typicel
entry may look like this:
@example
machine ftp.uni-erlangen.de
login ftp
password <your mail address> or <ftp>
macdef init
    bin
    cd pub/aminet
@end example
Note that on some machines it is possible to use the machine name
@samp{default} which meets all machines not listed in .netrc.


@node Mail
@section Getting files from a Mail server
@cindex Mail-server
Another way to get files is to use a mail server. This assumes that you can
send mail to Internet addresses and get mail from Internet hosts. It works
by sending a mail to the server specifying some commands, for example
send commands for the files you want. Important mail servers are
@example
ftpmail@@decwrl.dec.com
mailserver@@nic.funet.fi
mailserver@@leo.org
mrcserv@@janus.mtroyal.ab.ca
mail-server@@ftp.cs.tu-berlin.de
mail-server@@rtfm.mit.edu
ftp-mail@@uni-paderborn.de
@end example
@noindent
The most important commands are:
@table @strong
@item Help
Tells the server that you wish to get an Ascii file containing detailed
explanation how to use the server.
@item Limit <number>
Specifys that you wish to get not more than <number> Kbytes per mail.
Larger files get splitted into small pieces of at most <number> Kbytes which
are sent as separate mails each. Note that the mails may get larger because
of overhead.
@item Cwd <dir>
Sets the current working directory to <dir>. This directory is used by the
commands send and dir.
@item Index
will return a list of files and/or directories that the server offers. Note
that this may be @strong{very} large!
@item Index <item>
returns a list of files containing <item> in their names.
@item Dir [<dir>]
returns a list of the files and directories in the given directory.
@item Send <file1> <file2> @dots{} <fileN>
Tells the server to send the given files to you.
@item Begin
Tells the server to ignore all lines above this command.
@item End
Like Begin, but specifies to ignore the lines below. (A signature for
example!)
@end table
A typical session would be to send the following mail to the mail server:
@example
BEGIN
CD /pub/aminet/util/arc
SEND LhA_e138.run
END
@end example


